“I cried out and no one heard me” (2023)

In this video I’m addressing concerns about people not crediting me when reposting my art. 

Long story short: I don’t mind people reposting my artwork AS LONG AS you mention my name somewhere in the caption or in the post. 

It’s really upsetting to see people botch, edit, and add their watermark on my art while cutting out my name on the piece. I understand this is the risk that artiste take now on social media…but honestly this is simple internet etiquette. I can’t do much but spread the word to please ALWAYS CREDIT THE ARTIST!!! Whether it’s my work or anyone else’s, it’s the right thing to do. 

I appreciate those who have brought this to my attention by tagging me in these posts. I appreciate you all looking out for me in these ways. ❤️ And again, I’m incredible grateful for the support I’ve received over the years. I just want to be credited for my work, that’s all. 🥺

I’ve came across hundreds of these edits on the internet, mainly from tiktok and Pinterest. People are ripping apart my art with edits, their OWN WATERMARKS and filters. But the worst part is my name is not mentioned or credited anywhere. People making 30 second slideshows solely of my art, going viral, and not a single time my name was mentioned as the artist. 

I understand this is the risk of the internet…but at the same time I don’t think artists should allow people to walk all over them like this. It’s gotten to the point where a few people I’ve encountered did not believe I was the original artist and thought I was reselling “tiktok art”. 

I’m gonna be real, I feel so undervalued as an artist right now. So I wanted to address this. I can’t do a whole lot but all I’ll say is: PLEASE CREDIT MY NAME WHEN YOU REPOST MY ART. Please DO NOT edit my art like this and remove my signatures. 

I’m really grateful people are connecting with my art in these ways. But at the same time, I want to be credited for my work…I think any artist would. I get the whole “chat bubble narrative” thing is cool to visualize…but again, editing an artist’s work without their permission is very violating. This is not just some random clip art from Microsoft Word…But overall I’m not as upset with the edits, more so the fact I’m not being credited. 

If you see these edits or videos, please tag me so I can be aware. I really appreciate those who have been doing this. I do have a tiktok account…yes it is very small but people CAN tag me on there! I have an account!

“caregiver” (2023) 

The inspiration for this one has a cute story. ☺️ I’ve been working with children the last school year, but more recently with little ones. I had a young student who kinda saw me as mommy #2 and always wanted to hold my hand and be close. My job role doesn’t allow that, so I had to find a creative way to discuss boundaries. 

I allowed her to do a “pinky touch” instead while we walked in the hallways if that made her feel better, and she happily agreed. (And then, before you know it, I had like six of my kinder’s wanting to do “pinky touch” simultaneously with me. 😂😂) 

Cute story aside, working with youth has always been enjoyable, but this time around since the pandemic, it opened my eyes to generational trauma and how easily it continues. It also made me realize how such a small thing can greatly impact a child. It made me realize how important it is to be conscious and aware of these things, and a lot of people…aren’t. :( 

I left the childcare sector last month and returned to being a full-time artist (overwhelming in itself!) It really was a fun experience, but I’m ready to hone in again on creating, and the freedom feels good. 💚

“I am whole within my light” (2023)

Okay this message might not resonate with everyone, but I wanted to create an art piece on this. 

Remember: you are whole on your own. You do not need another soul or human to complete you. You ARE complete. 

Sometimes people forget this (even myself at one point) and think they NEED a person to complete them. Stand tall within your light. Fill your cup first. 

Soulmate connections are (of course) good and relationships are essential, but it’s important to remember you are a whole person and you don’t need another to complete you. 

Super random but I hope this connects with whoever needs this 💜

I’ve been asking myself this question these last few weeks. I wish humanity could see that we are truly all one- yes we all may have different religions, beliefs, and paths, but in reality we are all HUMAN. And when we choose to hurt each other, all we are doing is hurting ourselves, internally, on a soul level. Humanity needs more empathy. It is not wrong to feel empathy for children and civilians who are suffering in war-ridden areas. We can still feel empathy for these humans despite the “differences” that label us. 

I wish we could respect each other more. I also wish governments and people in power felt this way, instead of using innocent humans as chess pawns in their game of war. I understand human history is complex, and suffering will inevitably happen…but the things humanity could accomplish if we all tried to live by a higher state of living, of respect and empathy for ALL…now that would be a greater, better world. 

My heart is gutted watching violence across the world continue…watching innocent children die, people being taken hostage and tortured, entire families eradicated. My heart weeps for these people. 

A majority of my art speaks on mental health… what about the mental health of the young children in these areas? The PTSD and deep trauma that will take years to heal. 

The light will prevail through all of this. Together, we must have hope. 

Artwork: “Judgement Day” (2022)

Although my intentions are pure, I know some people on the internet will still take my words and interpret them as hate and pro-death, so comments are off.

If we don’t have hope, then who will?

Finally making a post about this sculpture! “The Healer” was completed this year, and stands just a tad bit over 7 feet tall!! (roughly 216 cm)

I decided to call this piece “The Healer” because throughout the making process (1.5 years), I felt so much had changed and I had learned/healed a lot within that time frame. I had written forgiveness letters and buried them inside the chest of the piece, in between the throat & the heart. It was the first time I made a ceremony out of the making process, and I appreciated that. I want to incorporate that type of energy more in my art practice. 

Swipe to the 2nd slide to read a little more about the piece. I have sooo much footage and have been meaning to make a video post too, so that is coming soon! In that video I will dive more into my thoughts regarding this piece. 

Thanks for reading 💙 as an artist, sharing our work is always super daunting, especially when it’s personal, so I appreciate all the people who are here. 🫶🏼

things 2023 taught me: 

✹ you never know when and where connections can be made. take risks.
✹ running multiple businesses & trying to stay afloat with another job is tough. tbh being your own boss is tough… you have to always show up and keep pushing, even when #’s are down and growth is stagnant. 
✹ trademarking multiple businesses is also costly as f… but absolutely necessary. gotta cover your grounds. and don’t wait too long. 
✹ blessings to anyone working with kids, especially the youngsters.🫡 educators deserve so much more respect. 
✹ focus on actually living and being in the present. enjoying and holding gratitude for the little things. and taking time for actual rest. very very important for good mental health. 
✹ accepting the reality that it’s going to take years to unpack the trauma and process it. but also understanding that at a certain point, I need to step out of the “hurt” energy and fully let it go. and that process is hard! 
✹ lastly, understanding that some years are going to be more about “learning lessons” than hitting milestones. and that’s totally okay. not every year is going to be a big one…but to still enjoy the process of it all, is important.
